id: pm-wjfa
title: "Marketing & positioning program: reposition pm as the repository-native project context engine"
description: "Program epic for the 2026-07 marketing/branding strategy: keep 'agent-native project management' as the searchable category, own 'repository-native project context engine' as the differentiated category, with 'context infrastructure for software work' as the long-term vision. Master brand = pm; CLI/MCP/SDK/Web/Packages are product surfaces."
type: Epic
status: open
priority: 1
tags[5]: branding,docs,growth,marketing,positioning
created_at: "2026-07-13T09:28:19.572Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-13T09:33:29.814Z"
author: maintainer-agent
estimated_minutes: 2400
acceptance_criteria: Category statement + brand architecture ratified via ADR before any public copy changes; all child workstreams either shipped or explicitly dispositioned; no public surface still leads with command counts or 'Git-native project management CLI' as the primary descriptor
value: "Product maturity (1300+ commits, dozens of releases) far exceeds awareness (single-digit stars); positioning/distribution/proof gap, not a feature gap"
outcome: "Every public surface leads with one consistent category, doctrine, and installation path; agents and humans understand what pm is within one screen"
why_now: External strategy review 2026-07-13 identified category compression as the top growth blocker; further promotion before fixing positioning wastes attention
risk: medium
confidence: high
dependencies[1]{id,kind,created_at,author,source_kind}:
  pm-doxj,related,"2026-07-13T09:28:19.572Z",null,null
notes[7]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-07-13T09:29:30.721Z",maintainer-agent,"(1) COMPETITIVE LANDSCAPE snapshot (research cutoff 2026-07-12; star counts move): Beads ~25.2k stars — owns \"persistent structured memory for coding agents\"; differentiate via ranked/evaluable context + evidence + plans + SDK governance, do NOT imitate the memory label. Task Master ~27.8k — strong distribution; its core/standard/full MCP tool tiers are worth adopting; its provider-heavy AI layer is not. Backlog.md ~6.1k, very active — leads with \"AI agents write the code. You review the tasks\" and human review checkpoints; match its clarity, differentiate on ranking/contracts/safety/evidence. CCPM ~8.3k — a simple process diagram (PRD->Epic->Task->Issue->Code) beats a feature list; pm needs an equally simple context lifecycle (the five stages). Vibe Kanban ~27.3k but sunsetting — hosted UI must not become the moat; keep pm Web optional. GitHub Spec Kit ~120k, OpenSpec ~60.3k, BMAD ~50.4k — specs are visible but do not preserve execution context; position pm as the execution-context layer that begins where spec workflows hand off (complement, never replace)."
  "2026-07-13T09:29:31.154Z",maintainer-agent,"(2) INDUSTRY TRENDS grounding the strategy (with sources): (a) agentic development is normal repo activity — studies across 128k+ projects and a 932k-agentic-PR dataset (arxiv 2601.18341) => agents are the hero audience, humans review/govern. (b) MCP is the common connection layer; official MCP Registry in preview (modelcontextprotocol.io/registry/about) => publish verified registry metadata, treat MCP as distribution infrastructure not identity. (c) portable Agent Skills (SKILL.md, agentskills.io) are a second distribution layer => derive Claude/Codex skills from ONE canonical portable source. (d) tool-selection accuracy degrades with tool-set size (arxiv 2606.30317, Jun 2026) => 28 tools should be the available maximum, not the default surface. (e) more context is not better — oversized/auto-generated instruction files can lower success and raise cost (arxiv 2606.15828); our own GH issue found repeated tags = ~43 percent of one real pm context brief => this IS the opening for \"retrieved and ranked on demand, not pasted wholesale\". (f) MCP does not solve trust/least-privilege (arxiv 2605.24248) => market existing capabilities/trust-modes/sandbox/preflight as \"extensible without becoming ungovernable\"."
  "2026-07-13T09:29:31.616Z",maintainer-agent,"(3) GROWTH METRICS framework. North star: weekly successful context-assisted work cycles (orient/search/next -> claim or plan -> work+evidence -> validate -> close/handoff). Acquisition: GitHub visitors, README install clicks, npm installs, MCP Registry installs, plugin-marketplace installs, skills installs, source-by-client, demo completion. Activation: install ok, init ok, first context/next ok, integration doctor passes, first reuse-or-create, first claim, first MCP call. Value: recommendation accepted, blocked item avoided, duplicate avoided, budgeted handoff, plan materialized, evidence linked, validated close, eval thresholds passed. Retention: repo active at 7/30 days, agent returns across sessions, repeated claim-to-close cycles, handoff/resume frequency, multiple authors, package/profile retention. Ecosystem: external authors, community/verified packages, install success, preflight pass rate, SDK example completion. Trust: docs-drift checks, doctor pass rate, plugin/runtime version mismatch, unsupported-Node failures, over-budget context packets, lock conflicts + recovery. Telemetry stays opt-in and privacy-preserving (current config already supports opt-in, source segmentation, hashed author identity)."
  "2026-07-13T09:29:32.128Z",maintainer-agent,"(4) DO-NOT-DO fence (explicit anti-goals from the strategy — cite this note before proposing any of these): no new generic handoff feature before promoting/unifying pm brief prompt + pm context-pack; no new Kanban UI before making pm Web visible/coherent; no separate independently-versioned @unbrained/pm-sdk package merely for branding (keep /sdk subpath canonical; tiny compat re-export only after measured demand); do not expose all MCP tools by default; no huge generated AGENTS.md files (keep repo guidance tiny, detail lives in skills/pm guide); never lead with TOON/vector stores/command counts/extension counts; never make the local-first core require a hosted service; no productivity-percentage claims before a reproducible public benchmark; do not market pm as replacing every spec/issue/planning tool (\"execution-context layer\" is the credible position); no Discord until GitHub Discussions volume supports it (empty server = negative social proof); do not rename package or binary."
  "2026-07-13T09:29:32.552Z",maintainer-agent,"(5) EXACT METADATA COPY (ratify via the category ADR, then apply verbatim). GitHub About: \"Repository-native project context for coding agents — ranked work, durable plans, evidence, history, CLI, MCP, and TypeScript SDK.\" npm description: \"Repository-native project context engine and TypeScript SDK for coding agents and software teams.\" Website title: \"pm — Project Context Engine for Coding Agents\". Meta description: \"Give coding agents the right project context: ranked next work, durable plans, dependencies, evidence, history, CLI, MCP, SDK, and optional Web UI.\" Social card: headline \"Project management is context management.\" subhead \"Give every coding agent the right context.\" GitHub topics / npm keywords: coding-agents, ai-agents, context-engineering, project-context, agent-memory, agent-skills, model-context-protocol, mcp-server, agentic-development, project-management, task-management, local-first, git-native, developer-tools, typescript, cli, workflow-engine, multi-agent. Because \"pm\" is generic, always pair it in titles with project context / coding agents / MCP / git-native / TypeScript SDK. BENEFIT-FIRST feature names: pm next = explainable next-work ranking; pm context = active project context; pm brief prompt = token-budgeted agent handoff; pm context-pack = portable project context pack; pm plan = durable executable planning; files/docs/tests links = evidence graph; comments/notes/learnings = project knowledge trail; JSONL history = replayable project memory; pm contracts = machine-readable agent contract; context evaluation SDK = context quality testing; claims+locks = safe multi-agent coordination; profiles+packages = governed workflow runtime; package doctor = extension trust and compatibility check."
  "2026-07-13T09:29:33.003Z",maintainer-agent,"(6) VISUAL IDENTITY + VOICE direction: avoid robot/brain/checkmark/Kanban-column logos. Core metaphor = a focus aperture selecting one node and its relevant neighborhood from a larger project graph (represents selection, relevance, deps, token compression, continuity). Wordmark: lowercase pm, mono/semi-mono, focus bracket around the m, one graph edge entering the p; must work as favicon/terminal icon/badge/social card. Visual vocabulary: focus brackets, selected vs de-emphasized nodes, dependency lines, diff/history trails, compact context cards, token-budget bars, evidence checks, annotated terminal output. Voice: precise, calm, evidence-oriented, slightly provocative, never magical. Good: \"Rank the next valid task and show why.\" / \"Every mutation is locked, atomic, and replayable.\" / \"No required hosted backend.\" Bad: \"Revolutionary AI-powered autonomous project management.\" / \"Enterprise-grade reliability.\" / \"Zero configuration for everything.\""
  "2026-07-13T09:33:29.814Z",maintainer-agent,"(7) AUDIENCE-SPECIFIC messaging (per-persona promise/proof/CTA — feeds the persona switcher in pm-69vv): CODING-AGENT USERS — problem: each session rediscovers state, picks blocked work, duplicates, loses reasoning; promise \"your agent starts with the work that matters — not a blank chat and not a full project dump\"; proof: pm next, search-before-create, session context injection, claims, durable plans, brief/handoff, evidence + close validation; CTA: install pm for your agent. MAINTAINERS/LEADS — problem: agents produce code faster than humans can verify intent/scope/coordination/completion; promise \"make agent work reviewable before, during, and after implementation\"; proof: plan approval, AC, ownership, dep graph, linked tests/files, close evidence, history + restore, Web review; CTA: pilot pm in one repository. MULTI-AGENT TEAMS — problem: same-work claims, ignored deps, incoherent handoffs; promise \"coordinate agents through shared project state rather than chat conventions\"; proof: atomic claim --next, ownership conflicts, lock safety, blocked/ready queues, human-gated decisions, append-only activity, dependency-aware ranking; CTA: run the multi-agent demo. SDK/PACKAGE AUTHORS — problem: every tool rebuilds storage/search/workflow/testing; promise \"build project-aware tools on one typed context runtime\"; proof: PmClient, typed primitives, plan API, ranking API, search/vector adapters, profiles+schema, test harness, manifest synthesis + preflight, least-privilege capabilities; CTA: build your first pm package. PLATFORM VENDORS — problem: need stable project context without one hosted PM provider; promise \"embed repository-native project context via SDK or MCP without a control plane\"; proof: stable contracts, JSON+TOON, narrow MCP tools, in-process SDK, local operation, custom search/ranking, governance policies; CTA: view the integration architecture."
body: "# Marketing & positioning program (source: external strategy review, 2026-07-13)\n\n## Central thesis\nDo not market pm harder as a project-management CLI. **Reclassify what pm already is**: the repository-native project context engine for coding agents and software teams. The implementation already moved past \"task tracker\" — durable work graph in the repo, explainable context ranking, claims/locks/deps coordination, plans/decisions/evidence/history, one context system across CLI/MCP/SDK/plugins/Web, and measurable context quality (nDCG, recall, continuity, token budgets).\n\n## Three-level category system\n| Level | Message |\n| --- | --- |\n| Familiar/searchable | Agent-native project management |\n| Differentiated product category | Repository-native project context engine |\n| Long-term vision | Context infrastructure for software work |\n\n- Philosophy (intellectual foundation): **Project management is context management.**\n- Product promise: **Give every coding agent the right project context.**\n- Campaign headline: **Your coding agent can write code. pm tells it what matters.**\n- Proof line: Stored in Git. Served through CLI, MCP, TypeScript SDK, and Web. Measured by context quality.\n\n## The five-stage product model (organizing structure for website, README, talks, demos, onboarding)\nCAPTURE -> RANK -> COORDINATE -> PROVE -> REMEMBER\n1. **Capture** — items/types/statuses/goals/AC/plans/decisions/deps/links: work becomes explicit project state, not transient chat.\n2. **Rank** — next/context/search/aggregate/semantic-hybrid retrieval + relevance scoring: the agent gets the most relevant work, not a project dump.\n3. **Coordinate** — claim/release, ownership, dependency readiness, atomic claim --next, locks, policies, hierarchy: multiple agents without silent collisions.\n4. **Prove** — linked files/docs/tests, test runs, expected/actual, validation, close reasons: completion backed by evidence, not agent confidence.\n5. **Remember** — append-only history, notes/comments/learnings, activity, restore, briefs, context packs: knowledge survives resets/sessions/handoffs.\n\n## Brand architecture\nMaster brand = **pm** (lowercase wordmark). Surfaces: pm CLI, pm MCP, pm SDK, pm Web, pm Packages. Technical identifiers unchanged: repo unbraind/pm-cli, package @unbrained/pm-cli, binary pm, SDK import @unbrained/pm-cli/sdk, MCP binary pm-mcp. Never use \"pm-cli\" as the product name in consumer-facing prose except where a repo/package identifier is required. Do NOT rename package or binary — compatibility and search equity are valuable; the problem is what the name is paired with.\n\n## Messaging pillars\n1. The right work — ready+important, explained, avoids blocked/owned work.\n2. Durable context — plans/decisions/deps/notes/learnings/history survive beyond one conversation.\n3. Safe coordination — claims, locks, atomic mutations, policy, dependency semantics.\n4. Evidence over confidence — closes against linked code/docs/tests/expected-results + replayable history.\n5. Context with a budget — sparse output, depth controls, briefs, context packs, evaluation.\n6. One context system, every interface — same state via CLI/MCP/SDK/plugins/packages/Web.\n\n## Category names to AVOID as primary (fence)\n\"AI project manager\" (autonomous-personality read) · \"agent memory\" (Beads owns it; understates workflow/evidence/governance) · \"task tracker for AI\" (too small) · \"MCP project manager\" (one transport) · \"context OS\" (too grand pre-category) · \"AI-powered PM\" (generic, implies model dependence) · \"CLI-first Jira replacement\" (frames around incumbents).\n\n## Competitive wedge\nNot local files alone (many have that). The defensible combination: **repository-native + explainable context selection + token budgets + evidence-backed execution + replayable history + typed extensibility.** Compete with: Beads, Backlog.md, Task Master's task layer, git-native trackers, homegrown Markdown/JSON ledgers. Complement: Spec Kit, OpenSpec, BMAD, IDE task panels, GitHub Issues/Jira/Linear as org systems of record. Ecosystem sentence: \"Use your preferred spec workflow to decide what to build. Use pm to keep the execution context correct while humans and agents build it.\"\n\n## Flagship existing assets to promote (build nothing new first)\n- **pm-brief** (compact deterministic agent briefs, ranked next work, token-budgeted handoff prompts) and **pm-context** (durable context packs for work + dependency neighborhoods) are near-perfect embodiments of the philosophy — treat as flagship agent outcomes, not catalog entries.\n- Claude Code plugin (28 MCP tools, 5 skills, 14 slash commands, 4 subagents, session-start context injection) and Codex plugin are primary acquisition surfaces — move above the fold.\n\n## Phased plan\n1. **Phase 1 — make the product understandable**: category+message hierarchy, README/homepage rewrite, GitHub About/topics/npm metadata, badge diet, terminology guide, generated counts, runtime-requirement consistency. MUST precede any promotional push.\n2. **Phase 2 — effortless agent installation**: canonical Agent Skills, MCP Registry record, tool profiles, universal setup, agent doctor, version-pinned plugins, agent project profile.\n3. **Phase 3 — provable differentiation**: ContextBench corpus+dashboard, context-cost regression tests, flagship pm-brief/pm-context promotion, dogfood case study, multi-agent demo, fair comparison/complement pages.\n4. **Phase 4 — ecosystem pull**: community package submission flow, verified badges, templates, external-author docs, showcases, GitHub Discussions.\n5. **Phase 5 — runtime reach**: standalone binaries/Homebrew/lower Node floor evaluation, cross-repo context, read-only public sharing, stable docs channel alongside daily CalVer.\n\n## North-star metric\n**Weekly successful context-assisted work cycles**: orient/search/next -> claim or plan -> work + link evidence -> validate -> close or hand off. More meaningful than command calls or stars. Full metrics framework in notes."
